WEBVTT

00:06.340 --> 00:07.570
‐ Lincoln,
we're five minutes out.

00:10.135 --> 00:11.345
You're already inside,
aren't you?

00:11.345 --> 00:13.180
‐ We've been chasing him
for five years.

00:13.180 --> 00:14.806
‐ Yeah, well, you can wait
five more minutes.

00:14.806 --> 00:17.017
[distant screaming]

00:17.017 --> 00:18.644
‐ Sounds of distress
coming from upstairs.

00:18.644 --> 00:19.686
[distant scream]

00:19.686 --> 00:20.812
He's got a victim with him.

00:20.812 --> 00:22.481
‐ Lincoln, wait for backup.

00:24.024 --> 00:27.027
[foreboding music]

00:27.027 --> 00:28.528
♪ ♪

00:28.528 --> 00:30.364
You ever consider
the possibility

00:30.364 --> 00:32.866
that someone out there
might be smarter than you?

00:32.866 --> 00:34.368
‐ I suppose
anything's possible.

00:34.368 --> 00:37.371
[muffled panicked speech]

00:37.371 --> 00:40.707
[soft beeping]

00:41.583 --> 00:45.879
Male victim, alive,
wired to a device with a timer.

00:45.879 --> 00:47.548
‐ A device?
You mean like a bomb?

00:47.548 --> 00:48.549
‐ [chuckles]
Yeah.

00:48.549 --> 00:50.008
Exactly like a bomb.

00:50.008 --> 00:51.343
You gonna tell me
how to defuse it?

00:51.343 --> 00:53.053
‐ What?
You don't.

00:53.053 --> 00:55.138
You wait for backup.
We're three minutes out.

00:59.226 --> 01:00.852
‐ He doesn't have
three minutes.

01:03.230 --> 01:06.191
I'm Detective Lincoln Rhyme.
I'm gonna get you out of this.

01:07.401 --> 01:09.570
Three wires,
red, white, and green,

01:09.570 --> 01:12.573
connecting the victim
to a serious‐looking canister.

01:12.573 --> 01:15.033
Everything means something
with the Bone Collector.

01:16.702 --> 01:19.705
[muffled speech]

01:19.705 --> 01:21.790
[beeping]

01:21.790 --> 01:24.751
[soft dramatic music]

01:24.751 --> 01:28.589
♪ ♪

01:28.589 --> 01:30.090
‐ Lincoln, talk to me.

01:30.090 --> 01:31.925
‐ We're okay.

01:31.925 --> 01:35.095
He used an old titanium dioxide
canister to make the bomb.

01:35.095 --> 01:36.597
It's a pigment
used to make ink.

01:36.597 --> 01:38.432
‐ Yeah,
that's a great fun fact, but‐‐

01:38.432 --> 01:40.392
‐ Specifically white ink,
so I cut the white wire.

01:41.935 --> 01:43.895
‐ The floor!
‐ What?

01:43.895 --> 01:45.564
‐ [screams]

01:54.573 --> 01:57.576
[soft music]

01:57.576 --> 01:59.786
‐ ♪ Everyday ♪

01:59.786 --> 02:01.788
♪ It's a‐getting closer ♪

02:01.788 --> 02:05.334
♪ Going faster
than a rollercoaster ♪

02:05.334 --> 02:07.961
♪ Love like yours will
surely come my way ♪

02:07.961 --> 02:10.297
‐ [pained groans]

02:10.297 --> 02:12.633
‐ ♪ A‐hey,
a‐hey hey ♪

02:12.633 --> 02:16.136
‐ Are you still clinging
to life, Lincoln?

02:16.136 --> 02:17.971
You can't even move.
[chuckles]

02:17.971 --> 02:20.974
‐ [grunting]

02:20.974 --> 02:23.644
‐ ♪ Love like yours will
surely come my way ♪

02:23.644 --> 02:25.937
Can you hear me?

02:27.648 --> 02:30.442
I hope you can.

02:30.442 --> 02:34.946
I want you
to hear the sound

02:34.946 --> 02:38.992
of you being
just not smart enough.

02:40.619 --> 02:43.288
Just too late.

02:46.375 --> 02:47.668
‐ No, wait!

02:47.668 --> 02:50.629
[distant sirens blaring]

02:52.339 --> 02:54.007
No, no, no!

02:54.007 --> 02:55.509
No, no, no, no!

02:55.509 --> 02:58.011
[groans]

02:58.011 --> 03:00.180
♪ ♪

03:00.180 --> 03:01.848
‐ ♪ Everyday seems
a little longer ♪

03:01.848 --> 03:03.350
[door thuds]

03:03.350 --> 03:05.018
♪ Every way,
love's a little stronger ♪

03:05.018 --> 03:06.311
‐ Spread out!

03:06.311 --> 03:07.854
Spread out
and search everything!

03:07.854 --> 03:09.648
Get me a medic!

03:09.648 --> 03:11.024
Medic!

03:11.024 --> 03:12.984
‐ We have an officer down.

03:12.984 --> 03:14.820
Come on, guys.
We need a medic.

03:14.820 --> 03:17.364
[radio chatter]

03:17.364 --> 03:21.034
‐ It's okay, pal.
You're gonna be okay.

03:21.034 --> 03:22.536
You're gonna be okay, buddy.

03:22.536 --> 03:25.580
‐ ♪ Love like yours will
surely come my way ♪

03:25.580 --> 03:28.375
‐ ♪ A‐hey,
a‐hey hey ♪

03:28.375 --> 03:33.171
♪ Love like yours
will surely come my way ♪

03:33.171 --> 03:34.631
♪ ♪

03:35.882 --> 03:37.050
‐ [laughs]

03:37.050 --> 03:38.885
Is that to clean
the sink or something?

03:38.885 --> 03:40.178
‐ It's a kale ginger smoothie.

03:40.178 --> 03:41.721
‐ Kale, oh.

03:41.721 --> 03:45.058
Is that the one that's like
spinach but with more fur?

03:45.058 --> 03:46.351
I am so late.

03:46.351 --> 03:47.853
‐ Oversleeping is
a sign of malnutrition.

03:47.853 --> 03:50.564
‐ Mm, actually, it's a sign of
studying all night

03:50.564 --> 03:52.399
after working overtime
to provide

03:52.399 --> 03:53.900
for my precocious,
kale‐drinking sister.

03:53.900 --> 03:56.069
‐ [laughs]

03:56.069 --> 03:59.197
‐ Okay, but, alas,
someone has to be

03:59.197 --> 04:01.074
the responsible adult.

04:02.367 --> 04:03.577
What am I forgetting?

04:03.577 --> 04:05.162
‐Oh, uh‐‐

04:07.080 --> 04:08.248
‐ Oh.

04:10.292 --> 04:11.543
Thank you.
‐ Mm‐hmm.

04:12.711 --> 04:15.213
Extra cream cheese?
‐ That's my girl.

04:15.213 --> 04:16.715
‐ Oh, and I got the mail.

04:18.091 --> 04:19.384
‐ Huh.

04:29.603 --> 04:30.937
‐ You okay?

04:30.937 --> 04:32.939
‐ Fine.

04:32.939 --> 04:34.775
Yeah.

04:36.902 --> 04:39.446
Make good choices, okay?

04:39.446 --> 04:40.405
‐ Okay.

04:44.075 --> 04:47.245
[overlapping chatter]

04:56.087 --> 04:59.257
‐ [snoring]

05:01.635 --> 05:05.555
‐ Hey, what do you think
you're doing?

05:08.934 --> 05:10.936
‐ You missed
our breakfast date.

05:10.936 --> 05:12.813
‐ Sorry, Amelia.

05:12.813 --> 05:14.105
I had a long night.

05:14.105 --> 05:17.108
‐ I feel you.

05:17.108 --> 05:18.777
‐ Cheers.
‐ Officer!

05:18.777 --> 05:20.821
Officer!
There's someone on the tracks.

05:20.821 --> 05:22.280
I'm trying to raise
the next rain,

05:22.280 --> 05:24.282
but the conductor,
he's not answering.

05:40.507 --> 05:43.677
[foreboding music]

05:43.677 --> 05:50.642
♪ ♪

05:52.352 --> 05:53.812
‐ Call the control office.

05:53.812 --> 05:57.023
Tell them to stop
all trains on this line.

05:57.023 --> 05:58.817
Go now!

06:00.694 --> 06:01.528
[radio crackles]

06:01.528 --> 06:05.031
I got a 10‐54
in the 6 line tunnel.

06:05.031 --> 06:06.533
Requesting ba‐‐

06:06.533 --> 06:07.701
[sharp feedback]

06:07.701 --> 06:08.702
Request‐‐

06:08.702 --> 06:09.828
[radio static]

06:09.828 --> 06:11.329
[sighs]
Damn it.

06:15.917 --> 06:18.837
[suspenseful music]

06:18.837 --> 06:25.802
♪ ♪

06:30.891 --> 06:33.894
[rumbling]

06:40.025 --> 06:41.568
Hey!

06:41.568 --> 06:43.737
[rumbling grows louder]

06:43.737 --> 06:44.988
Hey!

06:48.241 --> 06:50.368
Hey!

06:50.368 --> 06:52.078
Hey!
Hey!

06:52.078 --> 06:53.288
[gunshots]

06:53.288 --> 06:54.956
[breaks screeching]

06:54.956 --> 06:57.917
Stop the train!
Stop!

07:05.425 --> 07:08.053
‐ I know it's not PC
for me to say this, Sachs,

07:08.053 --> 07:09.929
but you're crazy,
certifiable.

07:09.929 --> 07:10.764
‐ I was trying to preserve

07:10.764 --> 07:12.390
the integrity
of the crime scene.

07:12.390 --> 07:14.267
‐ You know what ruins
the integrity of a crime scene?

07:14.267 --> 07:15.727
A cop splattered
all over the tracks.

07:15.727 --> 07:17.228
‐ You the one
who stopped that train?

07:18.938 --> 07:19.939
‐ That's right.

07:19.939 --> 07:21.274
‐ Yeah, I'm Detective Sellitto.

07:21.274 --> 07:23.276
This is my partner
detective Castillo.

07:23.276 --> 07:24.736
You think you can
come uptown with us?

07:24.736 --> 07:26.279
You just won yourself
a ticket to meet

07:26.279 --> 07:27.447
the great Lincoln Rhyme.

07:27.447 --> 07:30.241
‐ What?
You serious?

07:32.077 --> 07:34.579
‐ Wait, you're taking me
to meet Lincoln Rhyme?

07:34.579 --> 07:37.457
‐ Father, son, and holy ghost
of forensic criminalistics.

07:37.457 --> 07:39.292
‐ He does say so himself.

07:39.292 --> 07:42.128
‐ I read his book
when I was in the academy.

07:42.128 --> 07:43.630
I thought he was retired.

07:43.630 --> 07:45.423
‐ Yeah, well the crime scene
you found in that tunnel

07:45.423 --> 07:46.591
might just change that.

07:46.591 --> 07:48.760
You were first on the scene.
He's gonna wanna talk to you.

07:48.760 --> 07:51.805
‐ If you love getting berated
by a condescending prick,

07:51.805 --> 07:52.681
it's a real treat.

07:52.681 --> 07:56.935
‐ Lincoln's a good man.
He's just intense.

07:56.935 --> 07:59.646
‐ I promise you, if you do
what you're about to do,

07:59.646 --> 08:02.315
it'll be the biggest mistake
of your life.

08:02.315 --> 08:03.775
[synthesized boom]

08:03.775 --> 08:04.943
[game characters
grunting and thwacking]

08:04.943 --> 08:08.613
Oh, that's‐‐that's
a lot of blood.

08:08.613 --> 08:11.157
Sorry, kid, it's never easy
watching someone

08:11.157 --> 08:12.617
realize I'm the greatest.

08:12.617 --> 08:14.661
‐ Is it embarrassing
being an old man

08:14.661 --> 08:16.454
playing against teenagers?

08:16.454 --> 08:18.331
‐ Is it embarrassing
being a teenager

08:18.331 --> 08:20.208
getting murderlized
by an old man?

08:20.208 --> 08:21.501
‐ Lincoln, you have visitors.

08:21.501 --> 08:24.295
‐ Ah, gotta go, kid.
Read a book or something.

08:24.295 --> 08:25.755
‐ Come on, man.

08:32.512 --> 08:34.681
‐ Place looks different.
You move your bed?

08:34.681 --> 08:35.807
‐ Light's better on this side.

08:35.807 --> 08:38.977
Plus redecorating helps
with the stultifying descent

08:38.977 --> 08:41.479
into insanity that comes
from being bedridden.

08:41.479 --> 08:43.022
‐ You remember my partner.

08:43.022 --> 08:45.358
‐ Darren.
‐ Eric.

08:45.358 --> 08:47.694
‐ Right, sorry.
My memory, it's‐‐

08:47.694 --> 08:49.696
‐ Flawless, photographic.

08:49.696 --> 08:51.364
‐ [chuckles]

08:51.364 --> 08:54.868
Claire, didn't we talk about
how Sellitto,

08:54.868 --> 08:56.870
much like a vampire,
can only enter

08:56.870 --> 08:58.997
if you invite him in?

09:01.041 --> 09:03.043
‐ I'll get you some coffee.

09:03.043 --> 09:05.045
‐ Thank you, Claire.

09:05.045 --> 09:06.713
‐ You're gonna
wanna see this one.

09:06.713 --> 09:08.381
‐ That's what you said
the last time.

09:08.381 --> 09:10.341
‐ I'm telling you
you're gonna wanna see this.

09:10.341 --> 09:12.010
‐ And the time before.

09:15.889 --> 09:17.348
Wait.

09:19.392 --> 09:21.519
Son of a bitch.

09:21.519 --> 09:23.354
Victim was put into this alive?

09:23.354 --> 09:25.065
‐ A noose around his neck.

09:25.065 --> 09:26.733
Soon as he couldn't
hold himself up any longer,

09:26.733 --> 09:29.527
he choked.

09:29.527 --> 09:31.404
‐ Evidence left behind?

09:31.404 --> 09:32.906
‐ Three pieces.

09:34.908 --> 09:36.868
You can thank
Officer Sachs here

09:36.868 --> 09:39.412
for saving that evidence,
by the way.

09:39.412 --> 09:40.789
She jumped in front
of a subway car.

09:40.789 --> 09:41.790
‐ Really?

09:43.416 --> 09:44.417
You know that's crazy, right?

09:44.417 --> 09:46.753
‐ I'm not crazy.

09:46.753 --> 09:48.254
‐ Take it as a compliment.

09:48.254 --> 09:50.882
‐ Crazy is never
a compliment, sir.

09:53.718 --> 09:55.428
‐ What's your career track
Officer Sachs?

09:55.428 --> 09:57.722
Detective?
CSI?

09:57.722 --> 09:58.765
‐ No.

09:58.765 --> 10:00.767
Not interested in either one.

10:00.767 --> 10:02.894
‐ Going to patrol
the subway station

10:02.894 --> 10:04.104
the rest of your career, then?

10:04.104 --> 10:05.605
‐ There are worse jobs.

10:05.605 --> 10:07.232
‐ So then what exactly,
in your

10:07.232 --> 10:10.777
subway patrolling expertise,
made you think this evidence

10:10.777 --> 10:12.904
was worth risking
your life to save?

10:14.614 --> 10:17.117
‐ It looked important.

10:17.117 --> 10:19.911
Everything posed.

10:19.911 --> 10:21.788
Like whoever did this
is playing a game,

10:21.788 --> 10:23.915
and they wanted me to have
all of the pieces.

10:25.291 --> 10:26.417
‐ Well...

10:27.460 --> 10:28.628
You were right.

10:34.259 --> 10:36.052
‐ It's him, isn't it?

10:37.303 --> 10:38.638
The Bone Collector.

10:38.638 --> 10:40.598
The one and only.

10:42.142 --> 10:44.644
Which means the body
you found is only the first.

10:46.271 --> 10:47.772
Always three with him.

10:50.275 --> 10:52.152
Three bodies in a day.

10:52.152 --> 10:54.779
Three pieces of evidence
leading to the next location.

10:56.656 --> 10:58.324
He's already got
someone else out there

10:58.324 --> 11:01.619
awaiting a similar fate.

11:01.619 --> 11:03.997
‐ So, what do you say?

11:05.540 --> 11:07.000
‐ I'd say I'm ready
for another shot

11:07.000 --> 11:09.460
at the bastard
who put me in this bed.

11:09.460 --> 11:12.338
[suspenseful music]

11:12.338 --> 11:16.843
♪ ♪

11:24.360 --> 11:25.518
[soft dramatic music]

11:27.812 --> 11:34.152
♪ ♪

11:34.152 --> 11:35.820
‐ A crime scene.

11:37.030 --> 11:40.366
One body and signs of a second
that isn't here.

11:40.366 --> 11:42.827
What is here is more evidence

11:42.827 --> 11:44.704
than you will ever get
in the real world,

11:44.704 --> 11:47.540
and yet, with the answer
right under your noses,

11:47.540 --> 11:50.210
every one of you
is hopelessly oblivious.

11:50.210 --> 11:51.836
Welcome to the most elite

11:51.836 --> 11:53.379
forensics academy
in the country,

11:53.379 --> 11:55.215
built on the bedrock
of this city.

11:55.215 --> 11:58.343
Here method is a half measure.

12:01.888 --> 12:04.724
‐ Lincoln Rhyme, NYPD.

12:04.724 --> 12:06.559
You wanna be
a great detective, Lincoln?

12:06.559 --> 12:08.561
‐ I'm already great.

12:08.561 --> 12:10.021
I wanna be the best.

12:10.021 --> 12:11.522
‐ Oh.

12:11.522 --> 12:14.234
Sherlock Holmes is
the greatest detective

12:14.234 --> 12:16.027
in the history
of fiction.

12:17.237 --> 12:19.530
‐ Do you know what
his superpower was?

12:19.530 --> 12:22.242
It was his dedication.

12:22.242 --> 12:25.912
He examined
every fragment of his city,

12:25.912 --> 12:29.457
investigated not only
the world around him,

12:29.457 --> 12:32.210
but the history beneath.

12:32.210 --> 12:34.712
He dug deeper,
altered his perspective,

12:34.712 --> 12:37.882
scrutinized every detail.

12:37.882 --> 12:39.884
He studied every book,
every map,

12:39.884 --> 12:42.595
every pigeon in London
for fun.

12:44.430 --> 12:47.183
Who among you is cursed with
that kind of obsession?

12:51.229 --> 12:54.274
‐ Hey, I gave my report
to Detective Castillo.

12:54.274 --> 12:55.566
You need me for anything else?

12:55.566 --> 12:58.236
‐ Actually, yes.
Stick around for a few.

12:58.236 --> 13:01.114
Kate, Felix,
good of you to come.

13:01.114 --> 13:04.617
‐ Lincoln's old forensics team.
Should be interesting.

13:04.617 --> 13:06.286
‐ I don't do apologies well.

13:06.286 --> 13:07.954
‐ Felix and I want
to close the chapter

13:07.954 --> 13:10.123
on the Bone Collector
just as much as you do.

13:10.123 --> 13:11.833
‐ But things are gonna
be different this time.

13:11.833 --> 13:13.584
‐ We have ground rules.
‐ Ground rules?

13:13.584 --> 13:16.754
‐ No rushing me,
no berating me,

13:16.754 --> 13:18.631
no assuming that I'm going
to be two steps further

13:18.631 --> 13:19.924
than anybody else
in my job would be

13:19.924 --> 13:21.801
simply because
I'm an obsessive overachiever.

13:21.801 --> 13:24.053
‐ You analyzed the evidence
already, didn't you?

13:26.597 --> 13:28.599
‐ I'm almost finished.

13:28.599 --> 13:30.727
Plus I had them bring me
some mobile equipment.

13:32.478 --> 13:33.771
‐ How 'bout you?

13:33.771 --> 13:34.939
‐ I just want your respect.

13:34.939 --> 13:37.900
‐ No, I meant were you able
to make what I asked for?

13:39.986 --> 13:41.195
[device beeps]

13:41.195 --> 13:44.490
Voilà, you want the experience
of being at a crime scene

13:44.490 --> 13:45.908
without ever leaving your bed.

13:47.618 --> 13:49.662
2 8K cameras,
360 degree view,

13:49.662 --> 13:51.706
voice com through an earpiece.

13:51.706 --> 13:52.790
Am I putting this on Sellitto?

13:52.790 --> 13:55.334
‐ No, I want you to put it
on Officer Amelia Sachs.

13:55.334 --> 13:56.335
‐ I'm sorry.
Who?

13:56.335 --> 13:57.503
‐ What?

13:59.297 --> 14:00.506
‐ Hi.
‐ Hi.

14:00.506 --> 14:02.759
‐ Uh, could you give
us a minute?

14:07.138 --> 14:10.808
‐ As previously established,
I am not a detective or a CSI.

14:10.808 --> 14:13.519
‐ Which means you don't have to
unlearn any bad habits.

14:13.519 --> 14:14.854
You're a blank slate
with great instincts.

14:14.854 --> 14:16.355
‐ Is that another compliment?

14:16.355 --> 14:18.149
‐ I read your file.

14:18.149 --> 14:21.861
Amelia Grace Sachs‐‐beat cop
going for her PhD

14:21.861 --> 14:23.529
in criminal psychology.

14:23.529 --> 14:25.531
Sounds like you're just putting
in the required three years,

14:25.531 --> 14:27.492
so you can get in the FBI.

14:27.492 --> 14:29.869
And what?
Be a profiler?

14:29.869 --> 14:32.038
Just so you know,
profiling's about as useful

14:32.038 --> 14:33.915
as a Tarot deck when it comes
to catching killers.

14:33.915 --> 14:37.001
‐ I see, so I should be your
crime scene puppet instead.

14:37.001 --> 14:38.169
‐ Do you know how
the Bone Collector

14:38.169 --> 14:39.545
got his name?

14:39.545 --> 14:41.047
‐ He wrote a letter
to the department

14:41.047 --> 14:44.383
saying most people
are just piles of bones.

14:44.383 --> 14:45.885
Signed it "the Bone Collector."

14:45.885 --> 14:47.512
‐ He didn't send the letter
to the department.

14:47.512 --> 14:48.679
He sent it to me.

14:50.056 --> 14:52.016
He also sent me
a human bone once.

14:53.726 --> 14:55.686
The radius from a victim's arm,

14:55.686 --> 14:57.522
but that much
we kept out of the news.

14:57.522 --> 15:00.733
‐ And how is this supposed
to convince me to wear that?

15:00.733 --> 15:01.734
‐ I already know
you're gonna wear it.

15:01.734 --> 15:02.902
You're a criminal psychologist,
and this is

15:02.902 --> 15:07.365
the most infamous serial killer
in the last two decades.

15:07.365 --> 15:09.867
I just want you to know
how personal it can get.

15:11.035 --> 15:12.537
‐ Right.

15:12.537 --> 15:14.580
[screen beeps]

15:14.580 --> 15:16.124
‐ Should be up there now.

15:16.124 --> 15:18.251
Still working on the cloth,
but the powder is a mix

15:18.251 --> 15:20.878
of potassium nitrate
and finely ground shale,

15:20.878 --> 15:22.588
specifically, medium‐grade
metamorphic schist

15:22.588 --> 15:24.257
interleaved with quartz.

15:24.257 --> 15:25.716
Basically, a ground up boulder.

15:25.716 --> 15:28.594
‐ Potassium nitrate,
that's saltpeter.

15:28.594 --> 15:29.762
‐ Wait, what peter?

15:29.762 --> 15:31.097
‐ Gunpowder.
‐ Gunpowder.

15:31.097 --> 15:32.098
Or to be precise,

15:32.098 --> 15:34.433
an old‐fashioned accelerant
used in gunpowder.

15:34.433 --> 15:35.601
When Central Park
was first built,

15:35.601 --> 15:37.603
it was littered with boulders
which had to be blown up

15:37.603 --> 15:39.230
by gunpowder
and carried out.

15:39.230 --> 15:41.065
Our next victim
is in Central Park.

15:43.109 --> 15:46.028
Amelia, you ready to take
the body rig for a spin?

15:55.997 --> 15:57.665
‐ Everybody, fan out!

15:57.665 --> 15:59.333
Fan out, search the perimeter.

15:59.333 --> 16:02.253
[suspenseful music]

16:02.253 --> 16:07.133
♪ ♪

16:07.133 --> 16:10.094
‐ Every object,
every bench, every tree.

16:10.094 --> 16:13.639
Look for something out of place
just like at the train station.

16:13.639 --> 16:14.974
And look at the people.

16:14.974 --> 16:16.809
He's been known
to watch crime scenes.

16:16.809 --> 16:18.644
‐ Okay, am I looking
at people or objects?

16:18.644 --> 16:20.938
‐ How about both?
Think you can handle that?

16:20.938 --> 16:23.107
‐ Yeah, I was just asking.
‐ Hold up.

16:23.107 --> 16:24.150
What's that?
‐ What's what?

16:24.150 --> 16:26.277
I have no way of knowing
what you're looking at.

16:26.277 --> 16:27.236
‐ Turn to your left.

16:29.614 --> 16:31.824
No, not that far.

16:31.824 --> 16:34.118
I said turn,
not do triple axel!

16:35.620 --> 16:36.829
‐ Give her a moment.

16:36.829 --> 16:38.539
she's never had
to do this before.

16:38.539 --> 16:40.208
‐ Neither have I.

16:40.208 --> 16:43.002
‐ It's wool.

16:43.002 --> 16:45.671
Wool...

16:45.671 --> 16:47.798
From Canadian Arcott sheep
to be exact.

16:47.798 --> 16:50.843
[low ethereal rumble]

16:53.971 --> 16:55.848
‐ Are there sheep
in Central Park?

16:57.350 --> 16:59.185
‐ There used to be.

16:59.185 --> 17:01.520
Sheep Meadow,
middle of the park.

17:01.520 --> 17:02.772
Go east.

17:05.358 --> 17:07.193
‐ It's an open field.

17:07.193 --> 17:08.861
Do you really think they could
hide a victim there?

17:08.861 --> 17:10.029
‐ Move towards the field.

17:10.029 --> 17:11.989
Look for an access
road of some kind,

17:11.989 --> 17:13.991
tire tracks on the grass,
anything.

17:13.991 --> 17:15.868
How do you hide someone
in a park?

17:17.203 --> 17:20.831
You bury them.

17:24.669 --> 17:25.711
‐ Guys!

17:25.711 --> 17:27.880
‐ What do you got?

17:27.880 --> 17:29.882
‐ Right here, right here,
the pile.

17:29.882 --> 17:32.218
‐ Oh, let's go!
All hands, let's go!

17:36.722 --> 17:38.391
‐ Get in.
Get in.

17:38.391 --> 17:40.851
‐ Ah, over here!
Hey!

17:40.851 --> 17:41.894
Right here!
Right here!

17:41.894 --> 17:44.564
‐ [grunts]
Let's get some shovels!

17:44.564 --> 17:46.357
‐ Lincoln, you seeing this?

17:46.357 --> 17:49.318
[all grunting]

18:01.414 --> 18:02.290
‐ [gasps]

18:02.290 --> 18:04.917
‐ We got her.
Oh, Lincoln, she's alive.

18:04.917 --> 18:06.043
It's okay.

18:06.043 --> 18:09.255
[soft dramatic music]

18:09.255 --> 18:10.881
♪ ♪

18:10.881 --> 18:12.717
‐ [coughing]

18:13.926 --> 18:16.387
‐ You're okay.
I got you.

18:16.387 --> 18:17.722
It's okay.

18:26.703 --> 18:28.433
‐ She's unconscious,
but she's stable.

18:30.067 --> 18:30.985
We saved her.

18:30.985 --> 18:34.280
‐ Good, now get back
to the crime scene.

18:34.280 --> 18:36.449
One last victim
is out there somewhere.

18:36.449 --> 18:39.285
Always threes with
the Bone Collector, remember.

18:39.285 --> 18:42.121
Three victims, three pieces
of evidence left at each scene.

18:43.789 --> 18:45.291
We need to see what he left us.

19:04.477 --> 19:05.978
‐ I got it.

19:05.978 --> 19:08.272
‐ Murky liquid, a piece
of paper with ink on it,

19:08.272 --> 19:09.440
and fabric samples.

19:09.440 --> 19:11.651
‐ That's very in‐depth
analysis, Kate.

19:11.651 --> 19:12.943
‐ Ground rules, Lincoln.

19:12.943 --> 19:13.778
‐ Right.

19:13.778 --> 19:14.987
How long to process these?

19:14.987 --> 19:16.822
‐ I don't have
the right equipment here.

19:16.822 --> 19:18.449
I have to get them
to my real lab.

19:18.449 --> 19:19.617
Four hours, maybe less.

19:19.617 --> 19:21.243
‐ Make it less.
‐ Ground rules.

19:23.162 --> 19:26.207
‐ Now comes
the really terrible part.

19:26.207 --> 19:27.833
The waiting.

19:27.833 --> 19:30.670
It's all just blind speculation
until the labs come back.

19:30.670 --> 19:33.923
Evidence illuminates
and aligns all things.

19:35.466 --> 19:39.637
‐ Lincoln, why haven't you
done this before?

19:39.637 --> 19:41.180
Partner with someone.

19:41.180 --> 19:43.349
I can see how much
you love this stuff.

19:43.349 --> 19:44.266
‐ You know that saying

19:44.266 --> 19:46.018
"find what you love
and let it kill you"?

19:46.018 --> 19:47.520
‐ No.

19:47.520 --> 19:49.021
‐ Well, I loved what I did.

19:49.021 --> 19:52.983
For the right reasons,
too, at first.

19:52.983 --> 19:55.111
And then pride took over.

19:57.530 --> 19:58.656
See these screens?

19:59.865 --> 20:02.868
Twice a week, a doctor straps
me to an overpriced VR setup

20:02.868 --> 20:05.037
and tries to trick
my limbs into working.

20:05.037 --> 20:07.540
Some people
regain full mobility.

20:07.540 --> 20:10.167
I haven't so much as
wiggled my toes in three years.

20:11.544 --> 20:12.878
What I love
may not have killed me,

20:12.878 --> 20:15.715
but it did leave me
in this bed alone.

20:15.715 --> 20:19.510
‐ It's just you here?
No family or kids?

20:19.510 --> 20:21.721
‐ Just me and Claire
and a few regrets.

20:21.721 --> 20:23.222
‐ Claire's your only nurse?

20:23.222 --> 20:25.182
‐ Fired the first six
they sent me.

20:25.182 --> 20:26.058
‐ [laughs]

20:26.058 --> 20:27.727
‐ But Claire and I
understand each other.

20:27.727 --> 20:29.729
‐ Why's that?

20:29.729 --> 20:32.898
‐ She's got her own wounds
to heal from.

20:32.898 --> 20:35.359
Turns out the broken
take better care of the broken.

20:38.028 --> 20:40.197
‐ The girl we rescued
in the park, Tasha Johnson,

20:40.197 --> 20:41.741
she's awake.

20:41.741 --> 20:43.409
‐ Don't wait for me.

20:46.871 --> 20:48.748
‐ Were you already
in the crate,

20:48.748 --> 20:51.125
or did he put you inside
when you got there.

20:51.125 --> 20:52.585
‐ He's asking
the wrong questions.

20:52.585 --> 20:55.588
‐ Lincoln, watch your stress.
Relax.

20:55.588 --> 20:57.923
‐ Anything at all about him?
Anything.

20:57.923 --> 20:59.759
His face, his voice,
his‐‐

20:59.759 --> 21:02.094
‐ Amelia, witness statements
are inaccurate and unhelpful.

21:02.094 --> 21:04.263
Crime scenes are what matter.

21:04.263 --> 21:05.765
If she can't tell us where
she was taken from,

21:05.765 --> 21:06.932
we're wasting time.

21:06.932 --> 21:08.434
‐ I think
that's enough for now.

21:08.434 --> 21:09.602
‐ Understood, ma'am,

21:09.602 --> 21:10.936
but someone else
might be in danger.

21:10.936 --> 21:13.439
‐ Amelia, crime scene,
crime scene, crime‐‐

21:13.439 --> 21:15.357
‐ I watched my parents die.

21:19.278 --> 21:21.071
I was 14.

21:21.071 --> 21:23.407
We were eating dinner
at my favorite restaurant.

21:24.575 --> 21:27.244
Laskey's in Astoria.

21:30.498 --> 21:33.959
Our waitress' name was Julie,
a name I only remember

21:33.959 --> 21:38.422
because Julie's ex‐boyfriend
John showed up that night

21:38.422 --> 21:41.091
with a Glock 17
he'd bought that afternoon.

21:44.804 --> 21:47.640
You know the rest.

21:47.640 --> 21:52.770
John Whitehead shot 14 people
at Laskey's Restaurant.

21:52.770 --> 21:55.815
Killed seven.

21:55.815 --> 21:58.275
I don't remember much
from that time.

21:59.652 --> 22:02.780
If I'm being honest, I barely
remember my parents' funeral.

22:04.281 --> 22:08.160
But I can place myself
right back there

22:08.160 --> 22:10.329
in that corner booth
that night.

22:12.540 --> 22:15.292
The red leather.

22:15.292 --> 22:19.129
The smell
of my mother's perfume...

22:20.840 --> 22:24.301
As she leaned over
to shield me.

22:27.179 --> 22:30.850
You can place yourself
in the spot

22:30.850 --> 22:35.312
that he attacked you,
can't you?

22:40.860 --> 22:43.153
Everything after is a blur,
I know.

22:45.030 --> 22:49.368
But that one moment.

22:49.368 --> 22:51.954
‐ The alley.

22:55.875 --> 22:58.168
Behind the grocery.

23:00.838 --> 23:03.966
Three blocks south
of my place.

23:07.720 --> 23:10.180
‐ Okay.
It's okay.

23:10.180 --> 23:12.016
Thank you.

23:14.226 --> 23:17.730
There,
you got your crime scene.

23:17.730 --> 23:20.357
‐ I like her.

23:20.357 --> 23:22.026
‐ Me too.

23:28.842 --> 23:29.241
[foreboding music]

23:31.410 --> 23:35.456
♪ ♪

23:35.456 --> 23:36.624
‐ [sighs]

23:36.624 --> 23:37.958
Can't even see his face.

23:37.958 --> 23:39.877
‐ Go back.

23:41.545 --> 23:42.713
‐ I hate to say it,
but Darren

23:42.713 --> 23:43.589
might have
stumbled upon something.

23:43.589 --> 23:44.757
‐ Eric.

23:44.757 --> 23:47.593
‐ There, it's no accident
you can't see

23:47.593 --> 23:49.887
our friendly neighborhood
Bone Collector's face.

23:49.887 --> 23:52.890
Look how he purposely shielded
his face with his arm

23:52.890 --> 23:54.266
as if he knows exactly

23:54.266 --> 23:55.935
where the city
surveillance cameras are.

23:55.935 --> 23:57.436
‐ You think he has access
to that system?

23:57.436 --> 23:59.438
‐ It would explain
how he's so deftly avoided us

23:59.438 --> 24:00.439
all these years.

24:00.439 --> 24:01.899
‐ City surveillance employee?

24:01.899 --> 24:03.275
‐ We'll need a court order
to get that list.

24:03.275 --> 24:05.277
‐Yeah, I'll make a call,
get it expedited.

24:07.446 --> 24:08.948
‐ Hey,

24:08.948 --> 24:12.284
this is the closest
we've come to identifying him.

24:12.284 --> 24:13.744
Good work.

24:20.793 --> 24:24.463
‐ Rachel, listen,
I'm gonna be late tonight.

24:24.463 --> 24:25.631
‐ I think I might
be able to manage

24:25.631 --> 24:27.257
on my own for a few hours,

24:27.257 --> 24:30.803
even at the tender young age
of basically a legal adult.

24:30.803 --> 24:33.055
Love you.
‐ Love you.

24:34.640 --> 24:39.311
Brat.

24:39.311 --> 24:43.148
My sister, she's 16.

24:43.148 --> 24:44.483
I take care of her.

24:44.483 --> 24:46.276
‐ I raised my siblings too.

24:46.276 --> 24:47.486
I get it.

24:47.486 --> 24:48.654
‐ Hm.

24:48.654 --> 24:52.491
‐ That story
about your parents...

24:52.491 --> 24:53.659
That's why you became a cop?

24:53.659 --> 24:57.121
‐ It's why I was going to be
a criminal profiler, yeah.

24:57.121 --> 24:59.039
‐ Was?

24:59.039 --> 25:02.793
‐ The FBI rejected me.
Found out this morning.

25:02.793 --> 25:06.005
It's‐‐uh, well, I mean,
it's my fault, really.

25:06.005 --> 25:08.132
I lied on my application.

25:08.132 --> 25:09.842
‐ I knew it.

25:09.842 --> 25:12.803
Soon as I saw you, I said,
"She's a convicted felon."

25:17.349 --> 25:22.521
‐ I have PTSD and various
anxiety disorders.

25:22.521 --> 25:24.815
By the way,
having mental conditions

25:24.815 --> 25:27.026
does not disqualify you
from serving in the FBI.

25:27.026 --> 25:28.694
‐ No.

25:28.694 --> 25:31.530
‐ Hiding it does.

25:31.530 --> 25:33.157
‐ Yes.

25:33.157 --> 25:35.701
‐ I'm never lying
about it again.

25:35.701 --> 25:37.661
‐ You're never gonna
believe this.

25:39.705 --> 25:40.539
Lincoln, I got a hair.

25:40.539 --> 25:42.249
‐ A hair from
the Bone Collector?

25:42.249 --> 25:44.376
From Tasha's clothes
inside the right sleeve.

25:44.376 --> 25:46.170
Our guy's got Fabry disease.

25:46.170 --> 25:47.880
It's a rare enzyme deficiency
in the kidneys

25:47.880 --> 25:50.049
treated with an even rarer
medication called Galafold,

25:50.049 --> 25:51.884
traces of which
I found in the hair.

25:51.884 --> 25:53.218
‐ We have a list
of city employees yet?

25:53.218 --> 25:54.678
‐ Sellitto's guy
just got it to me.

25:54.678 --> 25:56.221
‐ Can you‐‐

25:56.221 --> 25:58.724
‐ Check all their insurance
records for anyone on Galafold?

25:58.724 --> 26:00.017
Yep, doing it now.

26:00.017 --> 26:01.518
‐ How exactly are you
getting this?

26:01.518 --> 26:03.187
‐ Very, very legally.

26:05.731 --> 26:08.067
Cross referencing
city surveillance employees

26:08.067 --> 26:10.194
with patients on Galafold.

26:11.570 --> 26:13.697
What do you say, guys?

26:13.697 --> 26:15.240
You ready to meet
the Bone Collector?

26:17.576 --> 26:19.870
‐ Robert O. Sturm.

26:19.870 --> 26:22.456
‐ Multiple arrests
for animal cruelty as a teen,

26:22.456 --> 26:23.373
attempted arson as an adult.

26:23.373 --> 26:26.210
‐ Checks the right boxes
for a serial killer.

26:26.210 --> 26:27.211
‐ Wait, hold up.

26:29.088 --> 26:31.256
He was in a mental institution
for four years.

26:31.256 --> 26:32.883
2013 to 2017.

26:32.883 --> 26:34.093
‐ Wait, but that means‐‐

26:34.093 --> 26:35.427
‐ It means Robert Sturm
was locked up

26:35.427 --> 26:37.596
when the Bone Collector
put me in this bed.

26:37.596 --> 26:40.265
‐ Sturm's patient files
say that he was

26:40.265 --> 26:42.768
obsessed with
serial killers, especially‐‐

26:42.768 --> 26:44.269
‐ He's a copycat.

26:45.938 --> 26:49.066
The real Bone Collector's
still out there somewhere.

27:08.460 --> 27:09.753
‐ [screams]

27:09.753 --> 27:11.130
‐ Boo.
‐ [sighs]

27:11.130 --> 27:13.632
‐ God, do you have to sneak up
on me like that?

27:13.632 --> 27:14.716
‐ The party's tomorrow,
you know.

27:14.716 --> 27:16.635
‐ I know, I just want
everything to be perfect.

27:16.635 --> 27:19.972
Let me be a little neurotic.

27:19.972 --> 27:22.391
[phone beeps]

27:25.143 --> 27:28.146
Who is it?

27:28.146 --> 27:29.982
‐ Work.

27:29.982 --> 27:31.483
I may have to go
into the office

27:31.483 --> 27:33.318
for a couple of hours.

27:33.318 --> 27:34.278
‐ Okay.

27:35.654 --> 27:37.614
‐ Sturm.
S‐T‐U‐R‐M.

27:37.614 --> 27:39.491
White male, 37 years old.

27:39.491 --> 27:40.951
‐ Requesting ESU, two teams...

27:40.951 --> 27:42.327
‐ Victim possibly
on the premises.

27:42.327 --> 27:43.996
‐ Block off 1/2 mile
around his neighborhood.

27:43.996 --> 27:45.873
‐ You guys stay here.
We'll call you.

27:45.873 --> 27:46.999
‐ You do that.

27:49.001 --> 27:50.460
Should have known
it wasn't him.

27:52.671 --> 27:54.840
‐ We saved a woman's life

27:54.840 --> 27:56.842
and tracked down
a serial killer

27:56.842 --> 27:58.343
in a day.

27:58.343 --> 28:00.846
I'm sorry it's not the guy
you wanted it to be, but‐‐

28:00.846 --> 28:02.097
‐ It's funny, really.

28:03.140 --> 28:05.475
Bone Collector wins
even when he's not playing.

28:05.475 --> 28:08.687
‐ It's not a game, Lincoln.

28:08.687 --> 28:11.189
These are people's lives.

28:11.189 --> 28:14.192
‐ Amelia, I tapped
into Sturm's PC, found a bunch

28:14.192 --> 28:16.111
of screenshots from
the city surveillance system.

28:18.989 --> 28:21.700
[foreboding music]

28:21.700 --> 28:23.035
♪ ♪

28:23.035 --> 28:24.161
He's watching you.

28:27.581 --> 28:30.250
‐ The real Bone Collector
used to get involved

28:30.250 --> 28:32.502
in the lives of cops
investigating him.

28:34.212 --> 28:38.175
So it makes sense
that Sturm would copy his MO

28:42.554 --> 28:45.724
♪ ♪

28:45.724 --> 28:47.392
Rachel.

28:47.392 --> 28:49.019
It's my sister.

28:52.898 --> 28:54.983
Come on, come on.

28:56.026 --> 28:59.196
[phone vibrating]

29:09.226 --> 29:10.624
‐ Preparing to breach
suspect's warehouse.

29:11.458 --> 29:13.335
Stay alert
for possible hostage inside.

29:16.088 --> 29:17.255
‐ [grunts]

29:17.255 --> 29:18.757
‐ Go, go!

29:18.757 --> 29:19.925
‐ NYPD!

29:19.925 --> 29:21.259
Police!

29:21.259 --> 29:23.220
Let's go!
Go!

29:27.766 --> 29:28.684
‐ You're clear here!

29:30.769 --> 29:32.354
‐ Clear, sir!

29:33.772 --> 29:36.274
‐ No sight of Sturm
or the girl,

29:36.274 --> 29:38.527
but you need to see this.

29:42.614 --> 29:44.950
‐ Run!

29:44.950 --> 29:46.284
‐ Go, go, go!

29:46.284 --> 29:49.746
[overlapping shouts]

29:55.293 --> 29:56.420
‐ Please tell me
you have Rachel.

29:56.420 --> 30:00.132
‐ Negative, no Sturm either.
The place was booby trapped

30:00.132 --> 30:01.466
It's an ash heap.

30:01.466 --> 30:03.635
We're on our way to Amelia's.
How's that going?

30:07.139 --> 30:08.932
‐ Amelia, can you hear me?

30:10.600 --> 30:11.560
Amelia?

30:12.811 --> 30:13.979
‐ Yes.

30:13.979 --> 30:15.605
‐ Somewhere in your apartment
is the evidence

30:15.605 --> 30:17.149
that can lead us to Rachel.

30:17.149 --> 30:18.734
‐ I'm right here with you.

30:21.611 --> 30:23.822
Remember, just breathe.

30:26.992 --> 30:29.911
‐ [breathing frantically]

30:33.373 --> 30:37.002
I didn't protect her.

30:37.002 --> 30:40.505
I'm supposed to protect her.

30:40.505 --> 30:42.507
‐ Amelia, listen to me.

30:42.507 --> 30:44.676
I understand everything
you're going through.

30:44.676 --> 30:48.180
‐ No, you don't.
No, you don't, Lincoln.

30:48.180 --> 30:50.682
You don't have a family.

30:50.682 --> 30:53.643
This is just
another game to you.

30:55.353 --> 30:57.189
‐ So let's win.

30:57.189 --> 31:00.317
Be the person who jumped
in front of the subway car,

31:00.317 --> 31:02.194
and I'll be the detective
who can find Rachel,

31:02.194 --> 31:04.446
but don't give up now.

31:09.868 --> 31:12.370
‐ Lincoln.

31:12.370 --> 31:14.081
Look in the crowd.

31:14.081 --> 31:16.875
Look in the crowd.

31:25.717 --> 31:27.844
‐ Amelia, no,
wait for backup!

31:44.903 --> 31:47.531
The dumpster behind you!

31:47.531 --> 31:48.824
‐ Hands above your head!

31:52.077 --> 31:53.912
Drop the gun.

31:53.912 --> 31:55.580
Drop the gun!

31:55.580 --> 31:57.624
Look, I don't wanna shoot you.

31:57.624 --> 31:59.584
I just wanna know
where my sister is.

31:59.584 --> 32:01.086
‐ He's not gonna
tell you anything.

32:01.086 --> 32:03.338
Shoot him now.

32:06.424 --> 32:07.759
‐ Tell me where she is!

32:07.759 --> 32:12.264
[gunshots]

32:12.264 --> 32:14.724
No.

32:20.438 --> 32:23.358
‐ You okay?

32:26.736 --> 32:27.779
Amelia, what are you doing?

32:27.779 --> 32:31.616
‐ Not giving up.

32:32.784 --> 32:35.787
There, everything I could find
in my apartment.

32:35.787 --> 32:37.164
‐ Got anything yet
on the evidence

32:37.164 --> 32:38.790
Sturm left us in Tasha's crate?

32:38.790 --> 32:39.624
‐ We're close.

32:39.624 --> 32:40.542
‐ The fabric samples
are just that.

32:40.542 --> 32:43.128
They are clothing swatches
on a steel ring.

32:43.128 --> 32:44.629
We got silk, velvet, cashmere.

32:44.629 --> 32:46.631
The liquid is New York City
tap water,

32:46.631 --> 32:48.758
but highly contaminated
with coliform‐‐

32:48.758 --> 32:50.468
‐ Suggesting the presence
of E. Coli bacteria.

32:50.468 --> 32:51.678
The sewers.

32:51.678 --> 32:55.473
‐ And the bit of paper, it's
from an ad in an old catalog.

32:56.641 --> 32:58.894
‐ I was able to sharpen it up.

33:01.980 --> 33:04.983
[suspenseful music]

33:04.983 --> 33:09.654
♪ ♪

33:09.654 --> 33:11.323
‐ This font was common
to the catalogs

33:11.323 --> 33:12.657
at the turn
of the 20th century.

33:12.657 --> 33:14.492
The full phrase
is "Ladies Mile."

33:14.492 --> 33:16.828
What is now known
as the Flatiron district.

33:16.828 --> 33:18.205
It was filled
with clothing stores

33:18.205 --> 33:19.998
for the carriage crowd.

33:19.998 --> 33:21.541
Uh, rich folks.

33:21.541 --> 33:23.668
‐ That makes sense for
the clothing fabrics, then‐‐

33:23.668 --> 33:27.964
‐ So Rachel's in the sewers
beneath Flatiron?

33:29.633 --> 33:31.801
‐ It's a big search area.

33:31.801 --> 33:33.011
‐ And it might not even
be the right area.

33:33.011 --> 33:36.681
I can't know for sure until
we figure out the final piece.

33:36.681 --> 33:38.016
‐ Well, a guess
from Lincoln Rhyme

33:38.016 --> 33:39.851
is good enough for me.

33:39.851 --> 33:40.685
Let's go.

33:40.685 --> 33:43.980
‐ Call us when you get
that last piece.

33:43.980 --> 33:45.190
‐ If they get enough cops
in that sewer,

33:45.190 --> 33:46.316
they could save her in time.

33:46.316 --> 33:47.525
‐ No, this is
his final flourish.

33:47.525 --> 33:48.860
He wouldn't make it this easy.

33:48.860 --> 33:52.530
There's no way in hell
they find her sister.

33:52.530 --> 33:54.449
It's up to us.

33:56.034 --> 33:57.994
[muffled whimpers]

34:01.915 --> 34:03.541
[whimpering]

34:10.828 --> 34:11.383
‐ This is the wrong book.

34:12.217 --> 34:13.051
‐ Silk, velvet, cashmere,
there's nothing.

34:13.051 --> 34:15.553
‐ They mean something.
Keep looking.

34:15.553 --> 34:18.556
[dramatic music]

34:18.556 --> 34:25.230
♪ ♪

34:25.230 --> 34:27.524
It's not the fabrics,

34:27.524 --> 34:29.734
it's the ring
holding them together.

34:29.734 --> 34:32.862
Claire, I need my maps.
Top row.

34:37.909 --> 34:39.411
No.

34:39.411 --> 34:40.412
No!

34:40.412 --> 34:41.663
Easy, there are antiques.

34:41.663 --> 34:44.291
‐ Lincoln, Amelia found this
on the floor of the apartment.

34:44.291 --> 34:45.959
‐ Keep flipping.

34:45.959 --> 34:47.752
‐ At first I thought it was
just asphalt from Sturm's shoe,

34:47.752 --> 34:48.753
but I looked closer,
and there is

34:48.753 --> 34:50.088
roofing adhesive on it.

34:50.088 --> 34:51.589
‐ That doesn't fit
with the sewer water.

34:51.589 --> 34:53.091
‐ No, it does because‐‐

34:53.091 --> 34:54.884
‐ Water from a neglected
rooftop water tower

34:54.884 --> 34:58.763
is every bit as dirty
as a sewer.

34:58.763 --> 34:59.931
‐ There.

34:59.931 --> 35:03.101
[stirring orchestral music]

35:03.101 --> 35:10.066
♪ ♪

35:11.610 --> 35:14.904
1896, the Siegel‐Cooper
building becomes

35:14.904 --> 35:16.573
the first steel‐framed
department store

35:16.573 --> 35:18.283
in the city‐‐largest
in the world.

35:18.283 --> 35:19.451
That's why he used

35:19.451 --> 35:20.785
the steel ring
to bind the fabrics.

35:22.120 --> 35:23.496
‐ Thank you.

35:23.496 --> 35:25.665
‐ Amelia,
she's not in the sewer.

35:25.665 --> 35:26.833
‐ What?
She's not?

35:26.833 --> 35:27.834
‐ She's inside a water tower

35:27.834 --> 35:29.628
on the rooftop of
the Siegel‐Cooper building.

35:29.628 --> 35:31.755
[water splashing]

35:31.755 --> 35:34.758
[suspenseful music]

35:34.758 --> 35:41.931
♪ ♪

35:59.491 --> 36:01.242
[muffled grunts]

36:08.667 --> 36:10.627
‐ Rachel!

36:20.178 --> 36:22.180
‐ Sellitto, we lost the feed.
Talk to me.

36:23.181 --> 36:25.350
‐ [gasping]

36:25.350 --> 36:26.351
[coughs]

36:26.351 --> 36:28.186
‐ They're all right.

36:28.186 --> 36:30.689
They're both all right.

36:30.689 --> 36:33.650
[soft triumphant music]

36:33.650 --> 36:40.782
♪ ♪

36:56.172 --> 36:58.883
‐ Couldn't have done it
without you, partner.

36:58.883 --> 37:01.553
Gotta admit, from time to time,
I actually miss you.

37:01.553 --> 37:03.722
‐ Gotta admit, I'd miss me too.

37:06.683 --> 37:10.228
Eric, nice work.

37:10.228 --> 37:10.979
‐ Likewise, sir.

37:13.898 --> 37:15.692
‐ Lincoln, you have
another visitor.

37:17.068 --> 37:18.236
‐ Chief Olsen.

37:18.236 --> 37:22.365
Lincoln,
impressive work yesterday.

37:22.365 --> 37:25.410
‐ Well, I didn't do it alone.

37:25.410 --> 37:27.412
‐ Officer Amelia Sachs, ma'am.

37:27.412 --> 37:28.872
‐ I've heard
great things, officer.

37:30.123 --> 37:32.625
I know you were disappointed
it wasn't him,

37:32.625 --> 37:35.378
but I want you to know
we've never given up the hunt.

37:35.378 --> 37:38.256
‐ You made me an offer
after my injury

37:38.256 --> 37:40.717
to keep working cases
as a civilian consultant.

37:40.717 --> 37:41.926
‐ The offer still stands.

37:41.926 --> 37:44.095
‐ I have one request.

37:44.095 --> 37:47.265
I'd like Officer Sachs to be my
point person in the department.

37:47.265 --> 37:48.183
If you're willing.

37:48.183 --> 37:50.226
I've been told
I'm not the easiest person

37:50.226 --> 37:53.062
to work with, but‐‐
‐ I'm in.

37:54.939 --> 37:57.275
The broken take better care
of the broken.

37:57.275 --> 37:59.360
Right?

38:01.112 --> 38:03.448
‐ Welcome back.

38:03.448 --> 38:06.951
‐ No one can come into contact
with another person without

38:06.951 --> 38:09.704
leaving something behind
and taking something with them.

38:10.997 --> 38:13.166
‐ The body's underneath us

38:13.166 --> 38:16.127
in a colonial access tunnel
built in 1784,

38:16.127 --> 38:20.799
sealed off by the city in 1904
right below this building.

38:20.799 --> 38:22.133
‐ How did you figure it out?

38:22.133 --> 38:25.303
‐ You told us day one,
"right under our noses."

38:25.303 --> 38:27.305
"Built on the bedrock
of this city"

38:27.305 --> 38:29.140
All the evidence pointed right
back here,

38:29.140 --> 38:31.100
so I bought every map
I could find

38:31.100 --> 38:33.978
of every old street,
tunnel, and dock in the city.

38:35.980 --> 38:38.483
"Every pigeon in London,"
right?

38:38.483 --> 38:41.820
‐ Well, despite my having
to spoon feed you,

38:41.820 --> 38:43.905
I'm glad someone's using
their head around here.

38:45.490 --> 38:48.159
Good job.

38:48.159 --> 38:49.786
Keep learning.

38:57.961 --> 38:59.337
[foreboding music]

38:59.337 --> 39:01.130
‐ Lincoln, right?

39:01.130 --> 39:03.174
‐ That's me.

39:03.174 --> 39:06.511
‐ What you did back
there‐‐tough act to follow.

39:06.511 --> 39:08.680
‐ Yeah, I know.

39:08.680 --> 39:09.806
Take it easy.

39:09.806 --> 39:16.813
♪ ♪

39:20.316 --> 39:21.651
‐ You don't know when to quit,
do you?

39:21.651 --> 39:25.530
‐ Landing a cheap shot
on the champ makes you lucky,

39:25.530 --> 39:27.365
not the new champ.

39:27.365 --> 39:29.033
‐ Hey, Camden,
put your mom on real quick.

39:29.033 --> 39:31.870
‐ But Dad‐‐
‐ Hey, just for a second.

39:31.870 --> 39:34.330
All right.
Mom.

39:37.750 --> 39:40.670
‐ You're aware he's got
that pesky homework thing

39:40.670 --> 39:41.671
every now and then, right?

39:41.671 --> 39:45.383
‐ I thought he
was back‐‐the Bone Collector.

39:45.383 --> 39:47.218
[solemn music]

39:47.218 --> 39:49.387
It wasn't him,
but it was a wake‐up call.

39:49.387 --> 39:52.557
He's still out there.

39:52.557 --> 39:54.559
I know they've been looking
for him, I just‐‐

39:54.559 --> 39:56.519
‐ You just wanna be
a part of it again.

39:56.519 --> 39:58.730
You got that look.

39:58.730 --> 40:00.732
It's been a long time
since I've seen that look.

40:00.732 --> 40:02.734
♪ ♪

40:02.734 --> 40:04.193
‐ If I go after him again‐‐

40:04.193 --> 40:06.571
‐ We're thousands
of miles away, Lincoln.

40:06.571 --> 40:08.489
We couldn't be any safer.

40:10.575 --> 40:13.411
I'll put Camden back on.

40:15.788 --> 40:17.290
‐ All right, old man,

40:17.290 --> 40:19.375
now it's my turn
to murderlize you.

40:20.543 --> 40:23.421
[tender music]

40:23.421 --> 40:26.090
Dad?

40:29.427 --> 40:32.096
‐ Wine tasting's
for snobs or hobbyists.

40:32.096 --> 40:34.766
If you want something
truly complex,

40:34.766 --> 40:36.267
you need a fine whiskey.

40:36.267 --> 40:38.603
‐ I swear he wasn't this
insufferable in New York.

40:38.603 --> 40:39.938
‐ I'll prove it.

40:39.938 --> 40:41.606
‐ I hope you guys
have a few hours.

40:41.606 --> 40:44.609
[jazz music]

40:44.609 --> 40:51.866
♪ ♪

41:08.591 --> 41:11.469
[foreboding music]

41:11.469 --> 41:18.559
♪ ♪

41:31.823 --> 41:34.826
‐ It's okay.

41:34.826 --> 41:37.078
It'll all be over soon.

41:46.129 --> 41:48.464
There's nothing like
the perfect gift

41:48.464 --> 41:51.259
for an old friend.

41:53.511 --> 41:55.138
[Buddy Holly's
"Everyday" plays]

41:55.138 --> 41:58.516
‐ ♪ Everyday,
it's a‐getting closer ♪

41:58.516 --> 42:01.853
♪ Going faster
than a rollercoaster ♪

42:01.853 --> 42:06.357
♪ Love like yours
will surely come my way ♪

42:06.357 --> 42:09.193
♪ A‐hey, a‐hey, hey ♪

42:09.193 --> 42:14.323
♪ Love like yours
will surely come my way ♪

42:48.566 --> 42:50.526
[shimmering swell]
